    =\n|network            = Netflix\n|released           = \n}}\n'''''Five Came Back''''' is an American documentary based on the 2014 book ''Five Came Back: A Story of Hollywood and the Second World War'' by journalist [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Agard|first1=Chancellor|title=Mark Harris' 'Five Came Back' Is Coming to Netflix as a Docu-Series|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/02/23/mark-harris-five-came-back-netflix-docu-series/|accessdate=February 28, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 23, 2017}}</ref> It was released as a stand-alone documentary in New York and Los Angeles, and as a three-part series on [[Netflix]], on March 31, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Harris' Five Came Back is coming to Netflix as a docu-series|url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/02/23/mark-harris-five-came-back-netflix-docu-series/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary focuses on five directors \u2013 [[John Ford]], [[William Wyler]], [[John Huston]], [[Frank Capra]], and [[George Stevens]] \u2013 whose war-related works are analysed by modern filmmakers, respectively [[Paul Greengrass]], [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Francis Ford Coppola]], [[Guillermo del Toro]],  and [[Lawrence Kasdan]]. [[Meryl Streep]], who serves as narrator, won the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator]] for her performance.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''Five Came Back'' explores the experiences of five U.S. film directors \u2013 [[John Ford]], [[William Wyler]], [[John Huston]], [[Frank Capra]], and [[George Stevens]] \u2013 and their frontline work during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Netflix series narrated by Meryl Streep to tell story of how Hollywood faced fascism during World War II|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-02-28/new-netflix-series-narrated-by-meryl-streep-to-tell-story-of-how-hollywood-faced-fascism-during-world-war-ii|website=Radio Times|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> It draws on over 100 hours of archival footage and is narrated by [[Meryl Streep]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: See the Trailer for Netflix's New Documentary About World War II and Hollywood|url=https://time.com/4677556/netflix-trailer-five-came-back/|website=Time|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> Each modern director discusses the impact and legacies of one of the five earlier directors: [[Steven Spielberg]] (Wyler), [[Francis Ford Coppola]] (Huston), [[Guillermo del Toro]] (Capra), [[Paul Greengrass]] (Ford), and [[Lawrence Kasdan]] (Stevens).\n\nNetflix is also streaming the 13 documentaries discussed in the film:<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Anne|title=How 5 Directors Returned from World War II to Make Their Best Movies |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/04/directors-world-war-ii-five-came-back-mark-harris-documentary-netflix-1201797195/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=IndieWire|date=April 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*''[[The Battle of Midway (film)|The Battle of Midway]]'' (1942, John Ford)\n*''[[Prelude to War]]'' (1942, Frank Capra)\n*''[[The Battle of Russia]]'' (1943, Frank Capra)\n*''Undercover: How to Operate Behind Enemy Lines'' (1943, John Ford)\n*''[[Report from the Aleutians]]'' (1943, John Huston)\n*''[[The Memphis Belle: A Story of a Flying Fortress]]'' (1944, William Wyler)\n*''[[The Negro Soldier]]'' (1944, Stuart Heisler; produced by Frank Capra)\n*''[[Tunisian Victory]]'' (1944, John Huston)\n*''[[Know Your Enemy: Japan]]'' (1945, Frank Capra)\n*''[[The Battle of San Pietro]]'' (1945, John Huston)\n*''Nazi Concentration Camps'' (1945, George Stevens)\n*''[[Let There Be Light (1946 film)|Let There Be Light]]'' (1946, John Huston)\n*''[[Thunderbolt (1947 film)|Thunderbolt]]'' (1947, William Wyler)\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on the 2014 book of the same name by [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Harris |first=Mark |title=Five Came Back : A Story of Hollywood and the Second World War |publisher=Penguin Press |date=2014 |isbn=9781594204302 |oclc=964586334 }}</ref> The filmmakers studied more than 100 hours of [[newsreel]] and archival footage, and more than 40 documentaries and training films created by the five directors during the war. They also reviewed 50 studio films by the directors and more than 30 hours of raw footage from their war films.<ref>{{cite news|title=VIDEO: First Look - New Netflix Documentary Series FIVE CAME BACK|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/VIDEO-First-Look-New-Netflix-Documentary-Series-FIVE-CAME-BACK-20170228|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=BroadwayWorld|date=February 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Director [[Laurent Bouzereau]], who has extensive experience documenting films and directors, introduced the idea of interviewing five current directors for the project.<ref name=\"varietyhow\">{{cite news|last1=Tapley|first1=Kristopher|title=Author Mark Harris on Turning 'Five Came Back' Into a Netflix Documentary|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/five-came-back-mark-harris-interview-1202006357/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Variety|date=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMeryl Streep recorded the narration for the documentary on January 17, 2017, the same day she received her 20th Oscar nomination (for ''[[Florence Foster Jenkins (film)|Florence Foster Jenkins]]'').<ref name=\"varietyhow\"/>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[69th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator|Outstanding Narrator]]\n| [[Meryl Streep]]\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/five-came-back|title=Five Came Back|website=Television Academy}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Composition for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special|Outstanding Music Composition for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special]]\n| [[Jeremy Turner (composer)|Jeremy Turner]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 3rd Critics\u2019 Choice Documentary Awards\n| Best Limited Documentary Series (TV/Streaming)\n| ''Five Came Back''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/critics-choice-documentary-awards-full-winners-list-1053727/item/best-documentary-critics-choice-documentary-awards-nominees-announced-1047774|title=Critics' Choice Documentary Awards: Full Winners List|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |total_width= |background=#B30505 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           =  The Mission Begins\n |DirectedBy      =[[Laurent Bouzereau]]\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    = The series looks at the backgrounds of the five directors as World War II begins and their motives for helping the war effort. John Ford's ''[[The Battle of Midway (film)|The Battle of Midway]]'' was approved directly by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] while Frank Capra fights to get ''[[Why We Fight]]'' made.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Combat Zones\n |DirectedBy      =Laurent Bouzereau\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    =The directors learn their vision for the films is not always permissible by the U.S. government.  Wyler is shocked by the racism he encounters against African American soldiers and refused to make a film recruiting black soldiers. Meanwhile, the films' racist depiction of the Japanese versus human depiction of the Germans causes worry for the War Department, which at that time planned to redistribute the [[Internment of Japanese Americans|Japanese-American population from internment camps]] into towns across the United States.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = The Price of Victory\n |DirectedBy      =Laurent Bouzereau\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    = The five directors return to Hollywood after the war but are forever haunted by what they saw. Ford goes on a drinking bender after filming the carnage at [[Normandy landings|D-Day]]. Stevens is wholly unprepared for the horrors of [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] and realizes he is not there to film propaganda but to capture evidence of crimes against humanity. Wyler, who lost his hearing during the war, fears his career is over. Huston chronicles soldiers suffering from [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] in the film ''[[Let There Be Light (1946 film)|Let There Be Light]]'', only to have it suppressed by the U.S. government.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n}}\n\n==Critical reaction==\n''Five Came Back'' has received largely critical acclaim. It has a 97% approval rating based on 37 reviews on review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Five Came Back: Miniseries|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/five_came_back/s01/|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|language=en|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the series 3.5 stars out of 4, writing, \"Arguably the best documentary ever made about Hollywood and wartime, ''Five Came Back'' is nirvana for movie lovers and a real eye-opener for anyone new to the subject.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Travers|first1=Peter|title='Five Came Back' Review: WWII Doc Is a Peerless Hollywood History Lesson|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-five-came-back-movie-review-w473846|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> David Sims of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' praised the series' relevance today, and stated that it should have been longer: \"Harris's book recognized that Hollywood often shapes our perception of reality more than we know, and that the recruitment of these directors by the U.S. military intertwined the film industry with sometimes-dangerous assumptions of truth and realism. ''Five Came Back is'', in the end, a compelling examination of propaganda\u2014its purpose, its effectiveness, and its drawbacks. These are all things that are worth keeping in mind in 2017, just as they were many decades ago.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sims|first1=David|title='Five Came Back' and the Frightening Power of Propaganda|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/04/five-came-back-and-the-frightening-power-of-propaganda/521736/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The Atlantic|date=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAllison Shoemaker, who reviewed each episode separately for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', gave \"The Mission Begins\" a B+ and graded both \"Combat Zones\" and \"The Price of Victory\" an A. Reviewing the final episode, she writes, \"It comes as no surprise that the conclusion to this remarkable series packs a wallop\u2014the previous episode ends with D-Day on the horizon, after all\u2014but what is surprising is how gracefully Laurent Bouzereau and Mark Harris link these monstrous and stunning events and truths to the art which followed them. Does tying Frank Capra's ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'' to George Stevens' experiences at [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] seem like a bit of a stretch? Sure, but somehow, it isn't. [[George Bailey (It's a Wonderful Life)|George Bailey]]'s story is also Capra's, and Ford's, and Wyler's. There's much that this hour makes clear, but chief among that crowded group is this: the experiences of and footage captured by these men changed the United States, the world, and the directors themselves in irrevocable ways.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=Five Came Back traces the transformation of an artist to an instrument of war|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/five-came-back-traces-transformation-artist-instru-253076|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=The directors grapple with bombings and bureaucracy in a gripping Five Came Back|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/directors-grapple-bombings-and-bureaucracy-grippin-253091|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=The stunning conclusion of Five Came Back makes us witnesses to both horror and joy|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/stunning-conclusion-five-came-back-makes-us-witnes-253127|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJohn Anderson in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' writes: \"Overall, the series is much like its story: mythic, adventurous, romantic. And real.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=John|title='Five Came Back' Review: When Directors Went to War|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-came-back-review-when-directors-went-to-war-1490897580|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Brian Tallerico, writing for [[RogerEbert.com]], called it a \"must-see\" and a \"cinephile and historian's dream come true.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tallerico|first1=Brian|title=Five Came Back Movie Review & Film Summary (2017) {{!}} Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/five-came-back-2017|accessdate=April 9, 2017|publisher=rogerebert.com|date=April 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New York Times]]'', Ben Kenigsberg writes, \"Above all, ''Five Came Back'' is an invitation to see more: It's hard to watch it without wanting to visit (or revisit) Wyler's ''[[Mrs. Miniver]]'' or Ford's ''[[They Were Expendable]].'' It's further proof, if any were needed, that these men weren't simply creating propaganda, but art that would endure.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kenigsberg|first1=Ben|title=Review: \u2018Five Came Back,\u2019 and Inspired the Likes of Spielberg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/30/movies/five-came-back-review.html|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKristin Hunt of ''Slashfilm'' questioned why the series did not address Ford's anti-semitism or Capra's admiration of [[Benito Mussolini]], but was generally positive, writing,  \"''Five Came Back'' is a testament to the power of cinema, and the moral implications that come with it. Was all this propaganda permissible? The documentary is sometimes afraid to truly grapple with that question. But when it does, it's gripping stuff.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Kristin|title=What to Watch After Five Came Back|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/what-to-watch-after-five-came-back/|accessdate=April 8, 2017|work=Slashfilm|date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge, chief film critic for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', was less enthusiastic, criticizing the series for leaving out the rich original research in Harris' book for the thoughts of the five current Hollywood directors, whose purpose he felt was merely a promotional gag.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debruge|first1=Peter|title=Film Review: 'Five Came Back'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/five-came-back-review-netflix-steven-spielberg-1202020658/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Variety|date=April 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|6587094}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/five_came_back/s01/ ''Five Came Back''] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n{{Frank Capra}}\n{{John Ford}}\n{{John Huston}} \n{{George Stevens}}\n{{William Wyler}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Netflix original documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about World War II]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Television series by Amblin Entertainment]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = Five Came Back\n|image              = Five Came Back (poster).jpg\n|caption            = \n|genre              = [[Documentary]]\n|creator            = \n|based_on           = {{Based on|''Five Came Back: A Story of Hollywood and the Second World War''|[[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]]}}\n|starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Francis Ford Coppola]]\n* [[Guillermo del Toro]]\n* [[Paul Greengrass]]\n* [[Lawrence Kasdan]]\n* [[Steven Spielberg]]\n}}\n|director           = [[Laurent Bouzereau]]\n|narrated           = [[Meryl Streep]]\n|theme_music_composer = [[Thomas Newman]]\n|composer           = [[Jeremy Turner (composer)|Jeremy Turner]]\n|country            = United States\n|language           = English\n|num_seasons        = 1\n|num_episodes       = 3\n|list_episodes      = #Episodes\n|executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Steven Spielberg]]\n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* [[Barry Diller]]\n* [[Angus Wall]]\n* Justin Falvey\n* Darryl Frank\n* Eli Bush\n* Jason Sack\n* Linda Carlson\n* Jason Sterman\n* Ben Cotner\n* Adam Del Deo\n*Lisa Nishimura\n}}\n|producer           = {{Plainlist|\n* Laurent Bouzereau\n* [[John Battsek]]\n}}\n|location           =\n|cinematography     = \n|editor             = Will Znidaric\n|camera             = \n|runtime            = 59-69 minutes\n|company            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Amblin Television]]\n* IACF Productions\n* [[Passion Pictures]]\n* Rock Paper Scissors Entertainment\n}}\n|distributor        = [[Netflix]]\n|picture_format     = \n|audio_format       =\n|first_run          = \n|first_aired        = \n|last_aired         = March 31, 2017\n|preceded_by        =\n|followed_by        =\n|related            = \n|website            = \n|website_title      = \n|production_website =\n|production_website_title =\n|image_size         =\n|image_alt          =\n|story              = \n|budget             =\n|network            = Netflix\n|released           = \n}}\n'''''Five Came Back''''' is an American documentary based on the 2014 book ''Five Came Back: A Story of Hollywood and the Second World War'' by journalist [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Agard|first1=Chancellor|title=Mark Harris' 'Five Came Back' Is Coming to Netflix as a Docu-Series|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/02/23/mark-harris-five-came-back-netflix-docu-series/|accessdate=February 28, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 23, 2017}}</ref> It was released as a stand-alone documentary in New York and Los Angeles, and as a three-part series on [[Netflix]], on March 31, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Harris' Five Came Back is coming to Netflix as a docu-series|url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/02/23/mark-harris-five-came-back-netflix-docu-series/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary focuses on five directors \u2013 [[John Ford]], [[William Wyler]], [[John Huston]], [[Frank Capra]], and [[George Stevens]] \u2013 whose war-related works are analysed by modern filmmakers, respectively [[Paul Greengrass]], [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Francis Ford Coppola]], [[Guillermo del Toro]],  and [[Lawrence Kasdan]]. [[Meryl Streep]], who serves as narrator, won the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator]] for her performance.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''Five Came Back'' explores the experiences of five U.S. film directors \u2013 [[John Ford]], [[William Wyler]], [[John Huston]], [[Frank Capra]], and [[George Stevens]] \u2013 and their frontline work during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Netflix series narrated by Meryl Streep to tell story of how Hollywood faced fascism during World War II|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-02-28/new-netflix-series-narrated-by-meryl-streep-to-tell-story-of-how-hollywood-faced-fascism-during-world-war-ii|website=Radio Times|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> It draws on over 100 hours of archival footage and is narrated by [[Meryl Streep]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: See the Trailer for Netflix's New Documentary About World War II and Hollywood|url=https://time.com/4677556/netflix-trailer-five-came-back/|website=Time|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> Each modern director discusses the impact and legacies of one of the five earlier directors: [[Steven Spielberg]] (Wyler), [[Francis Ford Coppola]] (Huston), [[Guillermo del Toro]] (Capra), [[Paul Greengrass]] (Ford), and [[Lawrence Kasdan]] (Stevens).\n\nNetflix is also streaming the 13 documentaries discussed in the film:<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=Anne|title=How 5 Directors Returned from World War II to Make Their Best Movies |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/04/directors-world-war-ii-five-came-back-mark-harris-documentary-netflix-1201797195/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=IndieWire|date=April 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*''[[The Battle of Midway (film)|The Battle of Midway]]'' (1942, John Ford)\n*''[[Prelude to War]]'' (1942, Frank Capra)\n*''[[The Battle of Russia]]'' (1943, Frank Capra)\n*''Undercover: How to Operate Behind Enemy Lines'' (1943, John Ford)\n*''[[Report from the Aleutians]]'' (1943, John Huston)\n*''[[The Memphis Belle: A Story of a Flying Fortress]]'' (1944, William Wyler)\n*''[[The Negro Soldier]]'' (1944, Stuart Heisler; produced by Frank Capra)\n*''[[Tunisian Victory]]'' (1944, John Huston)\n*''[[Know Your Enemy: Japan]]'' (1945, Frank Capra)\n*''[[The Battle of San Pietro]]'' (1945, John Huston)\n*''Nazi Concentration Camps'' (1945, George Stevens)\n*''[[Let There Be Light (1946 film)|Let There Be Light]]'' (1946, John Huston)\n*''[[Thunderbolt (1947 film)|Thunderbolt]]'' (1947, William Wyler)\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on the 2014 book of the same name by [[Mark Harris (journalist)|Mark Harris]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Harris |first=Mark |title=Five Came Back : A Story of Hollywood and the Second World War |publisher=Penguin Press |date=2014 |isbn=9781594204302 |oclc=964586334 }}</ref> The filmmakers studied more than 100 hours of [[newsreel]] and archival footage, and more than 40 documentaries and training films created by the five directors during the war. They also reviewed 50 studio films by the directors and more than 30 hours of raw footage from their war films.<ref>{{cite news|title=VIDEO: First Look - New Netflix Documentary Series FIVE CAME BACK|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/VIDEO-First-Look-New-Netflix-Documentary-Series-FIVE-CAME-BACK-20170228|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=BroadwayWorld|date=February 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Director [[Laurent Bouzereau]], who has extensive experience documenting films and directors, introduced the idea of interviewing five current directors for the project.<ref name=\"varietyhow\">{{cite news|last1=Tapley|first1=Kristopher|title=Author Mark Harris on Turning 'Five Came Back' Into a Netflix Documentary|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/five-came-back-mark-harris-interview-1202006357/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Variety|date=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMeryl Streep recorded the narration for the documentary on January 17, 2017, the same day she received her 20th Oscar nomination (for ''[[Florence Foster Jenkins (film)|Florence Foster Jenkins]]'').<ref name=\"varietyhow\"/>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[69th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Narrator|Outstanding Narrator]]\n| [[Meryl Streep]]\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/five-came-back|title=Five Came Back|website=Television Academy}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Composition for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special|Outstanding Music Composition for a Limited Series, Movie, or Special]]\n| [[Jeremy Turner (composer)|Jeremy Turner]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |total_width= |background=#B30505 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           =  The Mission Begins\n |DirectedBy      =[[Laurent Bouzereau]]\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    = The series looks at the backgrounds of the five directors as World War II begins and their motives for helping the war effort. John Ford's ''[[The Battle of Midway (film)|The Battle of Midway]]'' was approved directly by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] while Frank Capra fights to get ''[[Why We Fight]]'' made.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Combat Zones\n |DirectedBy      =Laurent Bouzereau\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    =The directors learn their vision for the films is not always permissible by the U.S. government.  Wyler is shocked by the racism he encounters against African American soldiers and refused to make a film recruiting black soldiers. Meanwhile, the films' racist depiction of the Japanese versus human depiction of the Germans causes worry for the War Department, which at that time planned to redistribute the [[Internment of Japanese Americans|Japanese-American population from internment camps]] into towns across the United States.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = The Price of Victory\n |DirectedBy      =Laurent Bouzereau\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Harris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    = The five directors return to Hollywood after the war but are forever haunted by what they saw. Ford goes on a drinking bender after filming the carnage at [[Normandy landings|D-Day]]. Stevens is wholly unprepared for the horrors of [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] and realizes he is not there to film propaganda but to capture evidence of crimes against humanity. Wyler, who lost his hearing during the war, fears his career is over. Huston chronicles soldiers suffering from [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] in the film ''[[Let There Be Light (1946 film)|Let There Be Light]]'', only to have it suppressed by the U.S. government.\n |LineColor       = B30505\n}}\n}}\n\n==Critical reaction==\n''Five Came Back'' has received largely critical acclaim. It has a 97% approval rating based on 37 reviews on review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Five Came Back: Miniseries|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/five_came_back/s01/|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|language=en|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the series 3.5 stars out of 4, writing, \"Arguably the best documentary ever made about Hollywood and wartime, ''Five Came Back'' is nirvana for movie lovers and a real eye-opener for anyone new to the subject.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Travers|first1=Peter|title='Five Came Back' Review: WWII Doc Is a Peerless Hollywood History Lesson|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-five-came-back-movie-review-w473846|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> David Sims of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' praised the series' relevance today, and stated that it should have been longer: \"Harris's book recognized that Hollywood often shapes our perception of reality more than we know, and that the recruitment of these directors by the U.S. military intertwined the film industry with sometimes-dangerous assumptions of truth and realism. ''Five Came Back is'', in the end, a compelling examination of propaganda\u2014its purpose, its effectiveness, and its drawbacks. These are all things that are worth keeping in mind in 2017, just as they were many decades ago.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sims|first1=David|title='Five Came Back' and the Frightening Power of Propaganda|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/04/five-came-back-and-the-frightening-power-of-propaganda/521736/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The Atlantic|date=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAllison Shoemaker, who reviewed each episode separately for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', gave \"The Mission Begins\" a B+ and graded both \"Combat Zones\" and \"The Price of Victory\" an A. Reviewing the final episode, she writes, \"It comes as no surprise that the conclusion to this remarkable series packs a wallop\u2014the previous episode ends with D-Day on the horizon, after all\u2014but what is surprising is how gracefully Laurent Bouzereau and Mark Harris link these monstrous and stunning events and truths to the art which followed them. Does tying Frank Capra's ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'' to George Stevens' experiences at [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] seem like a bit of a stretch? Sure, but somehow, it isn't. [[George Bailey (It's a Wonderful Life)|George Bailey]]'s story is also Capra's, and Ford's, and Wyler's. There's much that this hour makes clear, but chief among that crowded group is this: the experiences of and footage captured by these men changed the United States, the world, and the directors themselves in irrevocable ways.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=Five Came Back traces the transformation of an artist to an instrument of war|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/five-came-back-traces-transformation-artist-instru-253076|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=The directors grapple with bombings and bureaucracy in a gripping Five Came Back|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/directors-grapple-bombings-and-bureaucracy-grippin-253091|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shoemaker|first1=Allison|title=The stunning conclusion of Five Came Back makes us witnesses to both horror and joy|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/stunning-conclusion-five-came-back-makes-us-witnes-253127|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The A.V. Club|date=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJohn Anderson in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' writes: \"Overall, the series is much like its story: mythic, adventurous, romantic. And real.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=John|title='Five Came Back' Review: When Directors Went to War|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-came-back-review-when-directors-went-to-war-1490897580|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Brian Tallerico, writing for [[RogerEbert.com]], called it a \"must-see\" and a \"cinephile and historian's dream come true.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tallerico|first1=Brian|title=Five Came Back Movie Review & Film Summary (2017) {{!}} Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/five-came-back-2017|accessdate=April 9, 2017|publisher=rogerebert.com|date=April 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New York Times]]'', Ben Kenigsberg writes, \"Above all, ''Five Came Back'' is an invitation to see more: It's hard to watch it without wanting to visit (or revisit) Wyler's ''[[Mrs. Miniver]]'' or Ford's ''[[They Were Expendable]].'' It's further proof, if any were needed, that these men weren't simply creating propaganda, but art that would endure.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kenigsberg|first1=Ben|title=Review: \u2018Five Came Back,\u2019 and Inspired the Likes of Spielberg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/30/movies/five-came-back-review.html|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKristin Hunt of ''Slashfilm'' questioned why the series did not address Ford's anti-semitism or Capra's admiration of [[Benito Mussolini]], but was generally positive, writing,  \"''Five Came Back'' is a testament to the power of cinema, and the moral implications that come with it. Was all this propaganda permissible? The documentary is sometimes afraid to truly grapple with that question. But when it does, it's gripping stuff.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Kristin|title=What to Watch After Five Came Back|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/what-to-watch-after-five-came-back/|accessdate=April 8, 2017|work=Slashfilm|date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge, chief film critic for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', was less enthusiastic, criticizing the series for leaving out the rich original research in Harris' book for the thoughts of the five current Hollywood directors, whose purpose he felt was merely a promotional gag.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debruge|first1=Peter|title=Film Review: 'Five Came Back'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/five-came-back-review-netflix-steven-spielberg-1202020658/|accessdate=April 9, 2017|work=Variety|date=April 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|6587094}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/five_came_back/s01/ ''Five Came Back''] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n{{Frank Capra}}\n{{John Ford}}\n{{John Huston}} \n{{George Stevens}}\n{{William Wyler}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Netflix original documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about World War II]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Television series b